"1438","Lownde Hall, Butterwick, Lincolnshire, England":"Butterwick, Lincolnshire, England","York,Yorkshire,England":"York, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Boston, Lincolnshire,, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1410–1460":"1410–1460","1400–1454":"1400–1454","1410–Female":"1410–Deceased","1438–1474":"1438–1474","1375–1431":"1375–1431","1382–Female":"1382–Deceased","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1454":"1454","1431":"1431","1375":"1375","1474":"1474","1395":"1395","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Abt 1438":"about 1438","1438":"1438","Lownde Hall, Butterwick, Lincolnshire, England":"Butterwick, Lincolnshire, England","York,Yorkshire,England":"York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Boston, Lincolnshire,, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lound","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Lund  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lund","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Anders, Lars, Nils, Thor, Iver, Nels, Obert, Berger, Einer, Knute, Morten.","Scandinavian, German, and English: topographic name for someone who lived by a grove, Old Norse <i>lundr</i>; the word was adopted into northern dialects of Middle English and also into Anglo-Norman French. There are a number of places in England named with this word, as for example Lund in Lancashire, East Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire, Lunt in Merseyside, and Lound in Lincolnshire, Nottinghamshire, and Suffolk, and the surname may derive from any of these. As a Swedish surname it is probably most often ornamental.","German: habitational name from any of the places called Lund or Lunden in Schleswig-Holstein."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Lound was born in 1410, in Boston, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Alexander Lound, was 35 and his mother, Margaret of Romania, was 28. He had at least 1 daughter with Maud Cave. He died in 1460, in Butterwick, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1410–1460":"1410–1460","1400–1454":"1400–1454","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1438–1474":"1438–1474","1375–1431":"1375–1431","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1454":"1454","1431":"1431","1375":"1375","1474":"1474","1395":"1395","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Abt 1438":"umbes 1438","1438":"1438","Lownde Hall, Butterwick, Lincolnshire, England":"Butterwick, Lincolnshire, England","York,Yorkshire,England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Boston, Lincolnshire,, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"14